### ========================================
### GRACEFUL DEGRADATION DEMOS (for interview)
### These demonstrate partial failure handling
### ========================================

### DEMO 1: Pricing Unavailable (nl-NL + XYZ999)
### XYZ999 has forceUnavailable=true with reason "PRICING_ENGINE_MAINTENANCE"
### Expected: Product returned with pricing.available=false, pricing.reason="PRICING_ENGINE_MAINTENANCE"
GET http://localhost:8080/product-info?productId=XYZ999&market=nl-NL
Accept: application/json

###

### DEMO 2: Pricing Unavailable (pl-PL + ABC123)
### ABC123 has forceUnavailable=true with reason "NO_PRICE_FOR_MARKET"
### Expected: Product returned with pricing.available=false, pricing.reason="NO_PRICE_FOR_MARKET"
GET http://localhost:8080/product-info?productId=ABC123&market=pl-PL
Accept: application/json

###

### DEMO 3: Stock Unknown (pl-PL + ABC123)
### ABC123 does not exist in pl-PL availability data
### Expected: Product returned with availability.stockKnown=false
GET http://localhost:8080/product-info?productId=ABC123&market=pl-PL
Accept: application/json

###

### DEMO 4: Both Pricing AND Stock failures (pl-PL + ABC123)
### Same as above - shows multiple partial failures handled together
### Expected: pricing.available=false AND availability.stockKnown=false
GET http://localhost:8080/product-info?productId=ABC123&market=pl-PL&customerId=456
Accept: application/json

###

### DEMO 5: Customer not found falls back to STANDARD segment
### Customer "UNKNOWN" doesn't exist - should gracefully degrade
### Expected: customer.segment="STANDARD", customer.customerId=null
GET http://localhost:8080/product-info?productId=ABC123&market=de-DE&customerId=UNKNOWN
Accept: application/json

###

### DEMO 6: Everything works perfectly (de-DE + ABC123)
### All services return valid data
### Expected: All fields populated, pricing.available=true, availability.stockKnown=true
GET http://localhost:8080/product-info?productId=ABC123&market=de-DE&customerId=789
Accept: application/json

